// Java  Questions & Answers
// Source: QuizBit (regenerated from java_qa.md)
// Total: 107 questions

const allQuestions = [{"number": 1, "question": "Why is Java a platform-independent language?", "answer": "Java was designed so that programs don't depend on any specific hardware or operating system. The Java compiler translates source code into platform-independent bytecode, which can then run on any machine that has a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed."}, {"number": 2, "question": "Why is Java not a pure object-oriented language?", "answer": "Java supports primitive data types — byte, boolean, char, short, int, long, float, and double — that are not objects. Because not everything in Java is an object, it is not considered a pure object-oriented language."}, {"number": 3, "question": "What is the difference between heap and stack memory in Java, and how does Java use each?", "answer": "Stack memory is allocated per thread and has a fixed size. Heap memory is a larger region shared across the application and is allocated on demand at runtime.\n\nJava uses them as follows:\n\nLocal variables, method parameters, and method call frames live on the stack.\n\nObjects (and their fields) are allocated on the heap. The stack holds references that point to those heap objects.\n\nExample:\n\nclass Main {\n  public void printArray(int[] array) {\n    for (int i : array)\n      System.out.println(i);\n  }\n  public static void main(String args[]) {\n    int[] array = new int[10];\n    printArray(array);\n  }\n}\n\nHere, the main and printArray frames (and the local reference array) live on the stack, while the int[10] object itself is created on the heap."}, {"number": 4, "question": "Is Java a fully object-oriented programming language?", "answer": "No. Java is object-oriented in the sense that classes and objects are central to the language and almost everything you write lives inside a class. However, it is not considered a pure object-oriented language because it supports primitive data types (int, float, char, boolean, double, and so on) that are not objects and don't belong to any class hierarchy."}, {"number": 5, "question": "How is Java different from C++?", "answer": "Compilation model: C++ is compiled directly to machine code. Java source is compiled to bytecode and then interpreted (or JIT-compiled) at runtime by the JVM.\n\nPortability: Java programs are platform-independent — the same bytecode runs anywhere a JVM exists. A C++ binary only runs on the platform it was compiled for.\n\nPointers: C++ exposes raw pointers to the programmer. Java does not; it uses references internally and hides pointer arithmetic.\n\nMultiple inheritance: C++ supports multiple inheritance of classes. Java does not — it avoids the diamond problem by allowing multiple inheritance only through interfaces."}, {"number": 6, "question": "Pointers are used in C and C++. Why doesn't Java expose pointers?", "answer": "Pointers are powerful but easy to misuse — they can cause subtle bugs, memory corruption, and security issues if a program is allowed to read or write arbitrary memory addresses. Java was designed for simplicity and safety, so it hides pointers from the programmer and uses references instead. References can be reassigned and dereferenced, but they cannot be manipulated arithmetically. This adds a layer of abstraction, makes the garbage collector's job easier, and removes a large class of security vulnerabilities."}, {"number": 7, "question": "What is the difference between an instance variable and a local variable?", "answer": "An instance variable is declared inside a class but outside any method. It belongs to each instance of the class and represents part of that object's state. Every object gets its own copy, and modifying the variable on one object does not affect the others.\n\nExample:\n\nclass Athlete {\n  public String athleteName;\n  public double athleteSpeed;\n  public int athleteAge;\n}\n\nA local variable is declared inside a method, constructor, or block, and is only visible within that scope. Other methods of the same class cannot see it.\n\nExample:\n\npublic void athlete() {\n  String athleteName;\n  double athleteSpeed;\n  int athleteAge;\n}"}, {"number": 8, "question": "What default values are assigned to variables and instance fields in Java?", "answer": "Local variables have no default value — you must initialize them before use, or the compiler will produce a \"variable might not have been initialized\" error.\n\nInstance fields, on the other hand, are automatically initialized by the default constructor based on their type:\n\nReference types default to null.\n\nNumeric types (byte, short, int, long, float, double) default to 0 (or 0.0).\n\nboolean defaults to false.\n\nchar defaults to the null character ('\\u0000')."}, {"number": 9, "question": "What is data encapsulation?", "answer": "Data encapsulation is an object-oriented programming principle that bundles an object's data (its attributes) and the behavior that operates on that data (its methods) together into a single unit — typically a class.\n\nIt helps developers build modular software by keeping each object self-contained: an object exposes a public API and hides its internal state. Combined with access modifiers, encapsulation is also the basis of data hiding, which protects private fields from being modified directly by outside code."}, {"number": 10, "question": "What is the JIT compiler?", "answer": "JIT stands for Just-In-Time. It is the part of the JVM that improves runtime performance by compiling frequently-executed bytecode into native machine code on the fly.\n\nThe flow is roughly:\n\nThe javac compiler converts Java source (.java) into bytecode (.class).\n\nAt runtime, the JVM loads the .class files and, by default, interprets the bytecode.\n\nThe JIT compiler monitors which methods are called most often and compiles those \"hot\" methods to native code, applying optimizations as it goes.\n\nOnce compiled, the JVM executes the native code directly instead of interpreting the bytecode again, which significantly improves throughput."}, {"number": 11, "question": "What is the difference between the equals() method and the == operator in Java?", "answer": "== is a binary operator that compares the values on either side. For primitives this is a straightforward value comparison; for object references it compares the reference values themselves — that is, it returns true only when both references point to the same object in memory.\n\nequals() is a method defined on Object. Its purpose is to compare two objects for logical equivalence according to the class's own definition of equality. The default implementation in Object simply delegates to ==, but most standard classes (String, Integer, collections, and so on) override equals() to perform a content comparison.\n\nWhen you write your own classes, override equals() (and hashCode() alongside it) whenever you want two instances with the same field values to be considered equal."}, {"number": 12, "question": "How do you declare an infinite loop in Java?", "answer": "An infinite loop is one with no terminating condition (or a condition that is always true). Common idioms are:\n\nUsing for:\n\nfor (;;) {\n  // business logic\n  // break out when needed\n}\n\nUsing while:\n\nwhile (true) {\n  // business logic\n  // break out when needed\n}\n\nUsing do-while:\n\ndo {\n  // business logic\n  // break out when needed\n} while (true);"}, {"number": 13, "question": "Briefly explain constructor overloading.", "answer": "Constructor overloading means defining multiple constructors in the same class that share the name (the class name) but differ in the number or types of their parameters. The compiler picks the right one based on the arguments supplied at construction time.\n\nclass Hospital {\n  int variable1, variable2;\n  double variable3;\n\n  public Hospital(int doctors, int nurses) {\n    variable1 = doctors;\n    variable2 = nurses;\n  }\n  public Hospital(int doctors) {\n    variable1 = doctors;\n  }\n  public Hospital(double salaries) {\n    variable3 = salaries;\n  }\n}\n\nAll three constructors share the name Hospital but are distinguished by their parameter lists."}, {"number": 14, "question": "What is a copy constructor in Java?", "answer": "A copy constructor is a constructor that initializes a new object using the field values of an existing object of the same class.\n\nclass QuizBit {\n  String department;\n  String service;\n\n  QuizBit(QuizBit ib) {\n    this.department = ib.department;\n    this.service = ib.service;\n  }\n}\n\nNote that Java does not provide a copy constructor by default — you have to write one yourself. Alternatively, you can achieve a similar result through the Cloneable interface and the clone() method."}, {"number": 15, "question": "Can the main method be overloaded?", "answer": "Yes. You can declare any number of overloaded main methods in a class; the compiler accepts them like any other overloaded method. However, the JVM only recognizes one specific signature as the program entry point:\n\npublic static void main(String[] args)\n\nOnly that signature will be called when the class is launched. Any other overload is just a regular method that you would have to invoke explicitly.\n\nclass Main {\n  public static void main(String args[]) {\n    System.out.println(\"Main method\");\n  }\n  public static void main(int[] args) {\n    System.out.println(\"Overloaded int[] main\");\n  }\n  public static void main(char[] args) {\n    System.out.println(\"Overloaded char[] main\");\n  }\n  public static int main(double[] args) {\n    System.out.println(\"Overloaded double[] main\");\n    return 0;\n  }\n  public static void main(float args) {\n    System.out.println(\"Overloaded float main\");\n  }\n}"}, {"number": 16, "question": "Explain method overloading and method overriding with examples.", "answer": "Method overloading lets a class declare several methods with the same name as long as they differ in the number or types of their parameters. The compiler picks the right one at compile time based on the call site. Return type alone is not enough to overload a method.\n\nclass OverloadingHelp {\n  public int findArea(int l, int b) {\n    return l * b;\n  }\n  public int findArea(int l, int b, int h) {\n    return l * b * h;\n  }\n}\n\nBoth methods share the name findArea but differ in their parameter count: the first computes the area of a rectangle, the second the volume of a cuboid.\n\nMethod overriding happens when a subclass provides its own implementation of a method that is already defined in its superclass with the same signature. At runtime, the JVM dispatches to the subclass's version (this is dynamic polymorphism).\n\nclass HumanBeing {\n  public int walk(int distance, int time) {\n    return distance / time;\n  }\n}\n\nclass Athlete extends HumanBeing {\n  @Override\n  public int walk(int distance, int time) {\n    int speed = distance / time;\n    return speed * 2;\n  }\n}\n\nWhen walk() is called on an Athlete reference, the subclass's version runs and overrides the base class behavior."}, {"number": 17, "question": "Can a single try block be followed by multiple catch blocks in Java?", "answer": "Yes. A try block can be followed by any number of catch blocks, each handling a different exception type. The JVM evaluates them top-to-bottom and runs the first one whose type matches the thrown exception, so more specific exception types must appear before more general ones.\n\npublic class MultipleCatch {\n  public static void main(String args[]) {\n    try {\n      int n = 1000, x = 0;\n      int arr[] = new int[n];\n      for (int i = 0; i <= n; i++) {\n        arr[i] = i / x;\n      }\n    }\n    catch (ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException exception) {\n      System.out.println(\"1st block = ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException\");\n    }\n    catch (ArithmeticException exception) {\n      System.out.println(\"2nd block = ArithmeticException\");\n    }\n    catch (Exception exception) {\n      System.out.println(\"3rd block = Exception\");\n    }\n  }\n}\n\nIn this example the second catch runs because division by zero throws ArithmeticException before the loop ever reaches an out-of-bounds index. If x had been non-zero, the first catch would have run instead (the loop walks past index n - 1)."}, {"number": 18, "question": "Explain the final keyword applied to variables, methods, and classes.", "answer": "final is a non-access modifier that marks something as unchangeable.\n\nfinal variable: once assigned, the variable's value (or, for references, the object it points to) cannot be changed. If the variable is not initialized at declaration, it must be assigned exactly once — typically in a constructor.\n\nfinal method: a final method cannot be overridden by subclasses. Constructors cannot be marked final because constructors are not inherited in the first place — the compiler rejects this with \"modifier final not allowed here\".\n\nfinal class: a final class cannot be extended. It can still extend another class itself; the restriction is only that no one can subclass it."}, {"number": 19, "question": "Do final, finally, and finalize do the same thing?", "answer": "No — they are three unrelated language features that happen to share a prefix.\n\nfinal is a modifier that restricts inheritance, overriding, and reassignment. Marking a variable final makes it a constant:\n\nfinal int a = 100;\na = 0; // compile-time error\n\nfinally is a block that follows try (and optionally catch). Its body runs whether or not an exception was thrown — typically used for cleanup such as closing files or releasing locks:\n\ntry {\n  int variable = 5;\n}\ncatch (Exception exception) {\n  System.out.println(\"Exception occurred\");\n}\nfinally {\n  System.out.println(\"Execution of finally block\");\n}\n\nfinalize() is a method declared on Object that the garbage collector used to call on an object just before reclaiming it, giving the object a chance to release resources. It has been deprecated since Java 9 and removed in later versions in favor of try-with-resources and java.lang.ref.Cleaner."}, {"number": 20, "question": "Is it possible for the finally block to not be executed? If so, when?", "answer": "Yes. A finally block normally runs no matter what, but it can be skipped in a few situations:\n\nThe JVM is shut down before the finally block executes — for example, the try or catch block calls System.exit().\n\nA fatal error terminates the JVM (StackOverflowError, OutOfMemoryError beyond recovery, an unrecoverable native crash, etc.).\n\nThe thread executing the try block is killed or interrupted at the OS level."}, {"number": 21, "question": "What is the output of this Java program, and why?", "answer": "public class QuizBit {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    final int i;\n    i = 20;\n    int j = i + 20;\n    i = j + 30;\n    System.out.println(i + \" \" + j);\n  }\n}\n\nThis program does not run — it produces a compile-time error on the line i = j + 30, with the message \"variable i might already have been assigned\". Because i is declared final, it can be assigned exactly once, and that already happened on the line i = 20."}, {"number": 22, "question": "When do you use the super keyword?", "answer": "super refers to the immediate parent class and is used to reach into it from a subclass. The three common uses are:\n\nAccess a parent-class field that has been hidden by a same-named field in the subclass.\n\nInvoke a parent-class constructor (default or parameterized) from a subclass constructor — the call must be the first statement in the constructor body.\n\nInvoke a parent-class method that the subclass has overridden.\n\nThe example below shows all three:\n\npublic class Parent {\n  protected int num = 1;\n  Parent() {\n    System.out.println(\"Parent class default constructor.\");\n  }\n  Parent(String x) {\n    System.out.println(\"Parent class parameterized constructor.\");\n  }\n  public void foo() {\n    System.out.println(\"Parent class foo!\");\n  }\n}\n\npublic class Child extends Parent {\n  private int num = 2;\n\n  Child() {\n    super(\"Call Parent\"); // must be the first statement; calls the parameterized parent ctor\n    System.out.println(\"Child class default constructor\");\n  }\n  void printNum() {\n    System.out.println(num);       // prints 2 (Child's num)\n    System.out.println(super.num); // prints 1 (Parent's num)\n  }\n  @Override\n  public void foo() {\n    System.out.println(\"Child class foo!\");\n    super.foo(); // also call the parent's foo()\n  }\n}"}, {"number": 23, "question": "Can static methods be overloaded?", "answer": "Yes. Like any other method, a class can declare two or more static methods with the same name as long as their parameter lists differ."}, {"number": 24, "question": "Why is the main method static in Java?", "answer": "main is the entry point of a Java program, and the JVM has to be able to call it before any instance of the enclosing class exists. Static methods belong to the class itself rather than to an instance, so the JVM can invoke main by class name without first creating an object.\n\nIf main were an instance method, the JVM would need rules for which object to create and how to construct it, which would complicate startup and break the guarantee that exactly one entry point exists per launch."}, {"number": 25, "question": "Can static methods be overridden?", "answer": "No. A subclass can declare a static method with the same signature as one in its superclass, but that is called method hiding, not overriding. Overriding relies on dynamic dispatch, which is resolved at runtime based on the object's actual type. Static methods are resolved at compile time based on the declared (reference) type, so polymorphism does not apply."}, {"number": 26, "question": "What is the difference between static methods, static variables, and static classes in Java?", "answer": "Static methods and static variables belong to the class itself, not to any particular instance. Memory for them is allocated when the class is loaded, and they can be accessed using the class name without creating an object.\n\nFor example, the Math class provides static methods like Math.max(), Math.min(), Math.sqrt(), and Math.pow(). Array length, accessed as arr.length, is exposed through a special length field. In each case you don't need an instance to use them.\n\nStatic classes: a top-level class in Java cannot be static. Only a nested (inner) class can be declared static. A static nested class behaves like any other static member — it does not hold an implicit reference to an instance of the enclosing class and can be instantiated without one."}, {"number": 27, "question": "What is the main goal of garbage collection?", "answer": "The goal of garbage collection is to automatically reclaim the memory used by objects that are no longer reachable from the running program, freeing those resources for new allocations.\n\nThis makes memory management safer and easier for the developer, but it does not guarantee that memory will always be available — a program can still run out of heap space if it holds on to objects unnecessarily."}, {"number": 28, "question": "What is a ClassLoader?", "answer": "A ClassLoader is the part of the JRE responsible for loading class files into the JVM on demand. When the running program first references a class or interface, the ClassLoader locates the corresponding .class file, reads it, and makes it available to the JVM.\n\nFor example, when you write code that reads input from the console using java.util.Scanner, the ClassLoader loads the Scanner class the first time it is used."}, {"number": 29, "question": "Which part of memory — stack or heap — is reclaimed by garbage collection?", "answer": "The heap. Stack frames are released automatically when a method returns; garbage collection is only concerned with heap-allocated objects that are no longer reachable."}, {"number": 30, "question": "What is the difference between a shallow copy and a deep copy in Java?", "answer": "Both refer to ways of duplicating an object, but they differ in how much of the object graph is actually copied.\n\nclass Rectangle {\n  int length = 5;\n  int breadth = 3;\n}\n\nRectangle obj1 = new Rectangle();\n\nShallow copy: only the top-level reference is copied; both variables end up pointing at the same underlying object. Changes through one reference are visible through the other.\n\nRectangle obj2 = obj1; // shallow — obj1 and obj2 are the same object\n\nDeep copy: a brand-new object is allocated and each field is copied (recursively, when fields are themselves objects). The two objects are independent and modifying one does not affect the other.\n\nRectangle obj3 = new Rectangle();\nobj3.length = obj1.length;\nobj3.breadth = obj1.breadth;\n\nThe effect is easier to see in a small program:\n\nclass Rectangle {\n  int length = 5;\n  int breadth = 3;\n}\npublic class Main {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    Rectangle obj1 = new Rectangle();\n    // Shallow copy\n    Rectangle obj2 = obj1;\n    System.out.println(\"Before: obj2.length=\" + obj2.length + \", obj2.breadth=\" + obj2.breadth);\n    obj1.length = 10;\n    obj1.breadth = 20;\n    System.out.println(\"After:  obj2.length=\" + obj2.length + \", obj2.breadth=\" + obj2.breadth);\n  }\n}\n\nOutput:\nBefore: obj2.length=5,  obj2.breadth=3\nAfter:  obj2.length=10, obj2.breadth=20\n\nBecause obj2 references the same object as obj1, modifying obj1 also changes what obj2 sees. Replace the shallow assignment with a deep copy and obj2 keeps its original values:\n\nRectangle obj2 = new Rectangle();\nobj2.length = obj1.length;\nobj2.breadth = obj1.breadth;\n\nThe Object class also provides a clone() method that performs a (shallow) copy automatically for classes that implement Cloneable. A true deep copy still requires per-field handling for any reference-typed fields."}, {"number": 31, "question": "Apart from security, what are the reasons strings are immutable in Java?", "answer": "Several design goals motivate String immutability:\n\nString pool: Java keeps a pool of String literals on the heap so that identical literals can share a single instance, saving memory. Sharing is only safe if the shared object cannot change underneath its other users, so the pool requires immutability.\n\nThread safety: an immutable object can be shared freely between threads without any synchronization, since no thread can observe a partial update. This makes concurrent code involving strings much simpler.\n\nUse as map keys: HashMap and Hashtable cache a key's hash code. If a String key could be mutated after insertion, its hash code would change and the map would no longer be able to find the entry. Immutability guarantees the hash code stays valid."}, {"number": 32, "question": "What is a singleton class in Java, and how do you implement one?", "answer": "A singleton class is one for which only a single instance exists for the lifetime of the program; all clients share that one instance.\n\nA simple way to implement a singleton is to make the constructor private (so no one else can instantiate the class) and expose a static getInstance() method that lazily creates and returns the sole instance:\n\nclass WaterJug {\n  private int waterQuantity = 500;\n  private static WaterJug instance = null;\n\n  private WaterJug() {}\n\n  public int getWater(int quantity) {\n    waterQuantity -= quantity;\n    return quantity;\n  }\n\n  public static WaterJug getInstance() {\n    if (instance == null) {\n      instance = new WaterJug();\n    }\n    return instance;\n  }\n}\n\nCallers obtain the shared object through getInstance() and never construct it directly:\n\nWaterJug glass1 = WaterJug.getInstance();\nglass1.getWater(1);\n\nThe naive version above is not thread-safe. Common ways to make a singleton thread-safe are:\n\nDouble-checked locking with a volatile field.\n\nEager initialization at class-load time (a static final field).\n\nUsing an enum with a single constant — generally the simplest and safest approach in Java."}, {"number": 33, "question": "Which of these lines causes a compile-time error, and why?", "answer": "int[] n1 = new int[0];\nboolean[] n2 = new boolean[-200];\ndouble[] n3 = new double[2241423798];\nchar[] ch = new char[20];\n\nLine 3 fails to compile. The literal 2241423798 is larger than Integer.MAX_VALUE (2,147,483,647), and array sizes in Java must fit in a 32-bit int — the compiler reports \"integer number too large\".\n\nLines 1, 2, and 4 compile cleanly. Line 2 will, however, throw a NegativeArraySizeException at runtime: the JVM allocates the array on the heap and, finding that the requested size is negative, refuses and throws the exception."}, {"number": 34, "question": "What are the differences between String, StringBuffer, and StringBuilder?", "answer": "Storage: String literals live in the string pool. StringBuffer and StringBuilder objects live on the regular heap.\n\nMutability: String is immutable — every modification produces a new String. StringBuffer and StringBuilder are mutable; you can append, insert, and delete characters in place.\n\nPerformance: StringBuilder is the fastest of the three for repeated modification, because it is unsynchronized. StringBuffer is slower because every public method is synchronized. String is slowest for repeated mutation because each change allocates a new object.\n\nThread safety: StringBuffer is safe to use from multiple threads concurrently. StringBuilder is not — use it within a single thread. String is trivially thread-safe because it cannot change.\n\nSyntax:\n\n// String\nString first  = \"QuizBit\";\nString second = new String(\"QuizBit\");\n// StringBuffer\nStringBuffer third  = new StringBuffer(\"QuizBit\");\n// StringBuilder\nStringBuilder fourth = new StringBuilder(\"QuizBit\");"}, {"number": 35, "question": "What are the key differences between interfaces and abstract classes?", "answer": "Methods: an interface can only declare abstract methods (plus default and static methods since Java 8, and private methods since Java 9). An abstract class can mix abstract and concrete methods freely.\n\nFields: fields declared in an interface are implicitly public, static, and final — effectively constants. An abstract class can declare instance fields, including non-final and non-static ones.\n\nInheritance: a class can implement multiple interfaces but can extend only one (abstract or concrete) class. Interfaces are the standard way to combine behavior from multiple sources in Java.\n\nMember visibility: interface members are public by default. An abstract class can use any access modifier — public, protected, package-private, or private.\n\nDirection: an abstract class can implement an interface (it just doesn't have to implement all of its methods), but an interface can never extend a class.\n\nAbstract class example:\n\npublic abstract class Athlete {\n  public abstract void walk();\n}\n\nInterface example:\n\npublic interface Walkable {\n  void walk();\n}"}, {"number": 36, "question": "Will this program compile? If not, why, and how many errors will the compiler produce?", "answer": "abstract final class QuizBit {\n  public abstract void printMessage();\n}\nclass ScalarAcademy extends QuizBit {\n  public void printMessage() {\n    System.out.println(\"Welcome to Scalar Academy By QuizBit\");\n  }\n}\nclass ScalarTopics extends ScalarAcademy {\n  public void printMessage() {\n    System.out.println(\"Welcome to Scalar Topics By Scalar Academy\");\n  }\n}\npublic class Main {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    QuizBit ib = new ScalarTopics();\n    ib.printMessage();\n  }\n}\n\nThe program produces two compile-time errors:\n\nLine 1: \"illegal combination of modifiers: abstract and final\".\n\nLine 4: \"cannot inherit from final QuizBit\".\n\nabstract and final are mutually exclusive. abstract says the class is incomplete and must be subclassed; final says it cannot be subclassed. The two together make no sense, so the language rejects it."}, {"number": 37, "question": "What is a Comparator in Java?", "answer": "Suppose you have an ArrayList of employees (with fields like id, name, and salary) and you want to sort them by name. Calling Collections.sort() directly won't work because the JVM has no way to know which field to compare. Comparator solves this problem.\n\nComparator is a functional interface in java.util that declares a single method, compare(T a, T b). By providing your own Comparator (typically as a lambda or method reference), you tell the sort algorithm exactly how to order two elements:\n\nemployees.sort((a, b) -> a.getName().compareTo(b.getName()));\n\nComparators can also be chained (thenComparing) and reversed (reversed) to express more complex orderings."}, {"number": 38, "question": "\"In Java, static and private methods can be overridden.\" Comment on this statement.", "answer": "The statement is false in both cases.\n\nStatic methods belong to the class, not to an instance, so they are resolved at compile time based on the reference type. A subclass can declare a static method with the same signature as one in its superclass, and the compiler will accept it, but the behavior that results is called method hiding — not overriding. Dynamic dispatch does not apply.\n\nPrivate methods are not visible outside the class that declares them, so a subclass cannot even see them, let alone override them. A subclass method with the same signature is simply an independent method that happens to share a name."}, {"number": 39, "question": "How is HashSet different from TreeSet?", "answer": "Both HashSet and TreeSet implement the Set interface, are unsynchronized, and reject duplicate elements. They differ in a few important ways:\n\nImplementation: HashSet is backed by a hash table and stores elements in no particular order. TreeSet is backed by a red-black tree and keeps its elements sorted.\n\nPerformance: HashSet offers amortized O(1) time for add, remove, and contains. TreeSet's equivalent operations are O(log n), so HashSet is generally faster.\n\nEquality semantics: HashSet uses hashCode() and equals() to test for duplicates. TreeSet uses compareTo() (or a supplied Comparator) — two elements that compare as equal are considered duplicates, even if equals() would say otherwise.\n\nPermitted contents: HashSet allows a single null element and works with heterogeneous objects. TreeSet rejects null (and any element it cannot compare to the rest), throwing NullPointerException or ClassCastException at runtime."}, {"number": 40, "question": "Why is a character array preferred over a String for storing sensitive information?", "answer": "Strings in Java are immutable: once created, you cannot change or clear their contents. After you stop using a password held in a String, the object can sit in the heap (and possibly in the string pool) for an arbitrary amount of time before the garbage collector reclaims it. If a memory dump is captured during that window — by an attacker, a debugger, or a crash logger — the password may be exposed.\n\nA char[] is mutable. As soon as you are finished with it, you can overwrite each element (for example with Arrays.fill(buffer, '\\0')), which wipes the sensitive data from memory immediately and removes the window of exposure."}, {"number": 41, "question": "What does the JDK contain, and how does it relate to the JRE and the JVM?", "answer": "JDK (Java Development Kit): the package you install to write Java programs. It contains everything the JRE has, plus development tools such as the javac compiler, javadoc, jar, debugger, and so on.\n\nJRE (Java Runtime Environment): the runtime needed to execute compiled Java programs. It consists of the JVM plus the standard class libraries (java.lang, java.util, java.io, and so on) — for example, the System class with its println method comes from these libraries.\n\nJVM (Java Virtual Machine): a platform-specific component inside the JRE that loads bytecode and either interprets it or JIT-compiles it into native machine code for the host CPU. The JVM is the part that actually runs your program."}, {"number": 42, "question": "What are the differences between JVM, JRE, and JDK?", "answer": "Abbreviation:\nJDK — Java Development Kit\nJRE — Java Runtime Environment\nJVM — Java Virtual Machine\n\nDefinition:\n\nJDK is a complete software development kit for writing Java applications. It includes the JRE, the javac compiler, javadoc, the debugger, and other developer tools.\n\nJRE is the runtime package that provides the JVM plus the standard Java class libraries needed to execute a compiled Java program.\n\nJVM is a platform-dependent virtual machine that loads, verifies, and executes Java bytecode. It is specified abstractly by the Java Virtual Machine Specification and implemented by various vendors (HotSpot, OpenJ9, GraalVM, and others).\n\nPrimary purpose:\n\nJDK — write and compile Java code.\n\nJRE — run compiled Java code without development tools.\n\nJVM — provide the actual execution environment that the JRE wraps.\n\nRelationship: JDK contains the JRE, and the JRE contains the JVM. Installing the JDK gives you all three; installing just the JRE gives you the JVM and the runtime libraries but no compiler."}, {"number": 43, "question": "What are the differences between HashMap and Hashtable?", "answer": "Synchronization: HashMap is not synchronized, which makes it faster and a better choice for single-threaded code. Hashtable synchronizes every public method, which makes it safer for multi-threaded use but slower in general. For concurrent code today, ConcurrentHashMap is usually preferred over Hashtable.\n\nNull handling: HashMap permits one null key and any number of null values. Hashtable rejects null in both keys and values, throwing NullPointerException.\n\nOrdering: neither class guarantees iteration order, but HashMap has a subclass, LinkedHashMap, that preserves insertion order. Hashtable has no such subclass.\n\nStatus: Hashtable is a legacy class from Java 1.0 and is rarely used in modern code; HashMap (and ConcurrentHashMap for thread-safe use) is the recommended choice today."}, {"number": 44, "question": "Why is reflection important in Java?", "answer": "Reflection lets code inspect and manipulate other code — its own classes or those of the surrounding system — at runtime. You can ask what methods, fields, and annotations a class has, instantiate classes whose names are only known at runtime, and invoke methods through their reflective handles.\n\nFor example, suppose you have an object of unknown type and a method fooBar() you would like to call on it. Java's static type system would normally reject the call. Reflection makes it possible:\n\nMethod methodOfFoo = fooObject.getClass().getMethod(\"fooBar\", null);\nmethodOfFoo.invoke(fooObject, null);\n\nReflection underlies many frameworks (serializers, dependency-injection containers, ORMs, test runners), but it has real drawbacks:\n\nPerformance: reflective method calls are several times slower than direct calls.\n\nType safety: errors that would normally be caught at compile time only show up at runtime.\n\nDebuggability: reflective stack traces are deep and hard to read, so root-causing failures takes longer.\n\nPrefer non-reflective solutions when you can, and reach for reflection only when no static alternative exists."}, {"number": 45, "question": "What are the different ways to create a thread in Java?", "answer": "There are two classic ways to define a thread in Java.\n\nExtend the Thread class:\n\nclass QuizBitThreadExample extends Thread {\n  public void run() {\n    System.out.println(\"Thread runs...\");\n  }\n  public static void main(String args[]) {\n    QuizBitThreadExample ib = new QuizBitThreadExample();\n    ib.start();\n  }\n}\n\nImplement the Runnable interface (preferred, since it leaves your class free to extend something else):\n\nclass QuizBitThreadExample implements Runnable {\n  public void run() {\n    System.out.println(\"Thread runs...\");\n  }\n  public static void main(String args[]) {\n    Thread ib = new Thread(new QuizBitThreadExample());\n    ib.start();\n  }\n}\n\nCalling start() on a Thread creates a new call stack and asks the JVM to schedule the thread; the JVM then invokes run() on that new stack. Modern Java also offers higher-level options such as ExecutorService, CompletableFuture, and (since Java 21) virtual threads, which are usually preferable to managing Thread instances by hand."}, {"number": 46, "question": "What thread priorities does Java provide, and what is the default?", "answer": "Java exposes priorities as integers from 1 to 10. Three named constants on the Thread class describe the endpoints and the default:\n\nMIN_PRIORITY  = 1\nNORM_PRIORITY = 5\nMAX_PRIORITY  = 10\n\nA newly created thread inherits the priority of the thread that created it; the main thread starts at NORM_PRIORITY. Higher priorities are a hint that the thread should be favored by the scheduler, but the actual scheduling behavior depends on the underlying OS and is not guaranteed."}, {"number": 47, "question": "What is the difference between a program and a process?", "answer": "A program is a static set of instructions stored on disk — source code, or its compiled form — that describes how to perform some task.\n\nA process is a program in execution. When the operating system loads a program into memory, allocates resources to it (CPU time, file handles, address space), and begins running it, you have a process. The same program can run as many independent processes simultaneously."}, {"number": 48, "question": "What is the difference between the throw and throws keywords in Java?", "answer": "throw is a statement that actually raises an exception from within a method body. You hand it an exception instance, and execution jumps to the matching catch block (or out of the method if there isn't one).\n\nthrows appears in a method signature and declares which checked exceptions the method might propagate to its caller. Callers must then handle or re-declare those exceptions.\n\nExample:\n\nclass Main {\n  public static int testExceptionDivide(int a, int b) throws ArithmeticException {\n    if (a == 0 || b == 0)\n      throw new ArithmeticException();\n    return a / b;\n  }\n  public static void main(String args[]) {\n    try {\n      testExceptionDivide(10, 0);\n    } catch (ArithmeticException e) {\n      // handle the exception\n    }\n  }\n}\n\nHere testExceptionDivide uses throw to raise the exception when its preconditions fail and uses throws to announce that fact in its signature. main is then obliged to handle the exception (or re-declare it)."}, {"number": 49, "question": "What is the difference between a constructor and a method in Java?", "answer": "Purpose: a constructor initializes the state of a newly created object. A method exposes some behavior of the class — it acts on, or returns information about, an existing object (or the class itself, for static methods).\n\nReturn type: a constructor has no return type, not even void. A method must declare a return type; if it returns no value, that type is void.\n\nInvocation: a constructor is called implicitly by new when an object is created. A method must be called explicitly on an object (or class) after the object exists.\n\nDefaults: if you don't declare any constructor, the compiler adds a no-argument default constructor. There is no default method — if you don't write one, it simply doesn't exist.\n\nNaming: a constructor must have the same name as the class. A method can have any valid identifier as its name (including the class name, since a method is distinguished from a constructor by the presence of a return type).\n\nModifiers: a method may be marked final to prevent overriding. A constructor cannot be marked final because constructors are not inherited in the first place — the compiler rejects the combination with \"modifier final not allowed here\"."}, {"number": 50, "question": "Identify the output of this Java program and explain it.", "answer": "class Main {\n  public static void main(String args[]) {\n    Scaler s = new Scaler(5);\n  }\n}\nclass QuizBit {\n  QuizBit() {\n    System.out.println(\" Welcome to QuizBit \");\n  }\n}\nclass Scaler extends QuizBit {\n  Scaler() {\n    System.out.println(\" Welcome to Scaler Academy \");\n  }\n  Scaler(int x) {\n    this();\n    super();\n    System.out.println(\" Welcome to Scaler Academy 2 \");\n  }\n}\n\nThe program does not run — it produces a compile-time error. Both this(...) and super(...) are required to be the first statement of a constructor, so they cannot both appear in the same constructor body. Swapping the order doesn't help; whichever one comes second is illegal."}, {"number": 51, "question": "Does Java use pass-by-value or pass-by-reference?", "answer": "Java is strictly pass-by-value. There is no pass-by-reference in Java. The confusion arises because, when you pass an object, the value being copied is the reference to that object — so the called method receives its own reference variable that points at the same heap object.\n\nTwo scenarios make the distinction clear:\n\nCase 1 — the parameter is reassigned to a new object. The caller's reference is unaffected, because only the local copy changed. The original object is not modified.\n\nclass QuizBitTest {\n  int num;\n  QuizBitTest(int x) { num = x; }\n  QuizBitTest()      { num = 0; }\n}\nclass Driver {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    QuizBitTest ibTestObj = new QuizBitTest(20);\n    updateObject(ibTestObj);\n    System.out.println(ibTestObj.num); // prints 20\n  }\n  public static void updateObject(QuizBitTest ibObj) {\n    ibObj = new QuizBitTest(); // local reassignment only\n    ibObj.num = 50;\n  }\n}\n\nCase 2 — the parameter is used to mutate the shared object. Because both references point at the same instance, changes made through the parameter are visible to the caller.\n\nclass Driver {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    QuizBitTest ibTestObj = new QuizBitTest(20);\n    updateObject(ibTestObj);\n    System.out.println(ibTestObj.num); // prints 50\n  }\n  public static void updateObject(QuizBitTest ibObj) {\n    ibObj.num = 50; // mutates the shared object\n  }\n}"}, {"number": 52, "question": "What is the \"IS-A\" relationship in object-oriented Java?", "answer": "\"IS-A\" is another name for inheritance. When one class extends another, the subclass is considered a specialized kind of the superclass, and instances of the subclass can be used anywhere the superclass type is expected.\n\nFor example, suppose you have a TV class representing a traditional CRT television, and a SmartTV class that extends TV. SmartTV inherits everything TV has and adds new capabilities. You can therefore say SmartTV IS-A TV — every SmartTV is also a TV."}, {"number": 53, "question": "When you need to update a string many times, should you use String or StringBuffer?", "answer": "Prefer StringBuffer (or, in single-threaded code, StringBuilder). String is immutable, so each modification creates a brand-new String object — repeated concatenation produces a stream of throwaway objects that the garbage collector has to clean up. StringBuffer is mutable and dynamic, so successive append, insert, and replace operations all happen in place on a single backing array, with no extra allocations."}, {"number": 54, "question": "How do you exclude a field from serialization in Java?", "answer": "Mark the field with the transient keyword. Any field declared transient is skipped by the default serialization mechanism — the field is left out of the byte stream and is restored to its default value (null, 0, or false) on deserialization.\n\npublic class QuizBitExample {\n  private transient String someInfo;\n  private String name;\n  private int id;\n  // getters and setters\n}\n\nIn this example, name and id are serialized normally; someInfo is not."}, {"number": 55, "question": "What happens if static is missing from the main method's signature?", "answer": "The class still compiles — public void main(String[] args) is a perfectly valid method declaration. But when you launch the class, the JVM looks specifically for public static void main(String[] args). Finding none, it throws NoSuchMethodError: main at startup and the program never enters main."}, {"number": 56, "question": "What is the output of this program, and why?", "answer": "public class Main {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    System.out.println(\" Hello. Main Method. \");\n  }\n  public static void main(int[] args) {\n    System.out.println(\" Hello. Main Method2. \");\n  }\n}\n\nThe program prints \" Hello. Main Method. \". The JVM only recognizes public static void main(String[] args) as the entry point. The overload that takes int[] is a perfectly valid method, but the JVM ignores it at launch time. The second main would only run if some other code explicitly called it."}, {"number": 57, "question": "Can the main thread be made a daemon thread?", "answer": "No. The main thread is always a non-daemon (user) thread, and there is no way to convert an already-running thread between daemon and non-daemon states. Thread.setDaemon() must be called before the thread is started — by the time main is running, it is already too late."}, {"number": 58, "question": "What happens if you declare two main methods with the same signature in one class?", "answer": "It is a compile-time error: \"method main(String[]) is already defined in class X\". A class cannot have two methods with identical signatures — overloading requires the parameter lists to differ. Two identical main methods would be indistinguishable."}, {"number": 59, "question": "What is object cloning, and how do you achieve it in Java?", "answer": "Object cloning is the act of producing an exact copy of an existing object. In Java, a class must implement the marker interface java.lang.Cloneable and override the protected clone() method inherited from Object:\n\n@Override\nprotected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {\n  return super.clone();\n}\n\nIf you override clone() without implementing Cloneable, Object.clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException. Note that the built-in clone() performs a shallow copy — fields that are themselves references still point at the original objects. For a deep copy you have to clone (or otherwise duplicate) those nested objects yourself. In modern code, copy constructors or static factory methods are usually preferred over clone()."}, {"number": 60, "question": "How does an exception propagate through the call stack?", "answer": "When an exception is thrown, the JVM searches the current method for a catch block whose type matches. If one is found, control transfers there. If not, the method exits abruptly and the search continues in the caller, then that method's caller, and so on up the stack.\n\nThis unwinding continues until a matching catch is found. If the exception reaches the top of the stack (the main method, in a typical program) without being caught, the thread is terminated and the stack trace is printed; in the main thread this also ends the program."}, {"number": 61, "question": "What happens if exceptions in a program are not handled?", "answer": "Exceptions represent runtime conditions that the program needs to react to. Suppose an Android app written in Java tries to read a file from storage and the file is missing — that triggers an exception. If nothing in the program catches it, the exception propagates up to the thread boundary, the thread terminates, and the user typically sees a crash.\n\nMany of these conditions are outside the developer's control (the network is unavailable, a file is missing, a server returns an error). What the developer can control is how the program responds — by catching the exception and showing a helpful message, retrying, falling back to default behavior, or logging the failure so it can be investigated."}, {"number": 62, "question": "Must a try block always be followed by a catch block?", "answer": "No. A try must be followed by at least one of catch and finally — but it does not have to be catch. A try/finally pair (with no catch) is legal and is commonly used for cleanup code that must run even when an exception propagates out.\n\nIf you don't want to handle an exception locally, you can also let it propagate by declaring it in the enclosing method's throws clause."}, {"number": 63, "question": "Will the finally block execute when the try and catch blocks both end with a return statement?", "answer": "public int someMethod(int i) {\n  try {\n    // some statement\n    return 1;\n  } catch (Exception e) {\n    // some statement\n    return 999;\n  } finally {\n    // finally block statements\n  }\n}\n\nYes. finally runs whether the try block completes normally, throws, or returns early. The only way to skip it is to terminate the JVM (for example by calling System.exit()) before control leaves the try or catch."}, {"number": 64, "question": "Can a constructor of a class call another constructor of the same class?", "answer": "Yes. This is called constructor chaining, and it is done by calling this(...) as the first statement of the calling constructor. The arguments select which sibling constructor runs."}, {"number": 65, "question": "Arrays store their elements in contiguous memory, but ArrayList does not. Why?", "answer": "An ArrayList stores object references, and Java does not allow primitive types as the element type of a generic collection. The references themselves are kept in a contiguous backing array, but the actual objects they point to live wherever the heap allocator decided to put them — which is generally not contiguous.\n\nA plain Java array of a primitive type (such as int[]) does store its values contiguously in memory, because the values themselves are stored inline. The same is true of an array of references — the references are contiguous, even though the objects they point to are not."}, {"number": 66, "question": "Why is the first index of a Java array 0?", "answer": "Zero-based indexing makes element-address arithmetic cheaper. The JVM computes the address of element i in an array as:\n\naddress(i) = base_address + i * element_size\n\nFor an int array starting at address 100 (where each int takes 4 bytes), element 4 lives at 100 + 4 * 4 = 116, exactly where it should be.\n\nIf indexing were 1-based, the formula would need an extra subtraction:\n\naddress(i) = base_address + (i - 1) * element_size\n\nThat extra arithmetic on every element access adds up across millions of operations. Most C-family languages (including Java) adopted zero-based indexing for exactly this reason."}, {"number": 67, "question": "Why is removal from a linked list faster than from an array?", "answer": "In a linked list, removing the head or tail (or any node you already have a reference to) is just a couple of pointer reassignments — constant-time work. For example, removing the head is as simple as: head = head.next; the old node is now unreferenced and eligible for garbage collection.\n\nIn an array (or ArrayList), the elements have to stay contiguous to keep indexing constant-time. Removing an element from the middle or front therefore requires shifting every subsequent element one slot to the left, which is O(n) work. The constant for that shift is low, but it grows with the size of the array, while the linked-list operation does not."}, {"number": 68, "question": "How many overloads of add() and addAll() does the List interface provide, and what does each do?", "answer": "List provides two overloads of add and two overloads of addAll — four methods in total.\n\nboolean add(E e): appends the element to the end of the list. Returns true if the list was modified.\n\nvoid add(int index, E e): inserts the element at the specified index, shifting any existing elements to the right.\n\nboolean addAll(Collection<? extends E> c): appends every element of c to the end of the list, in the order returned by c's iterator. Returns true if the list was modified.\n\nboolean addAll(int index, Collection<? extends E> c): inserts every element of c starting at the specified index, shifting existing elements to the right."}, {"number": 69, "question": "How does an ArrayList grow dynamically, and how is it implemented internally?", "answer": "An ArrayList is backed by an ordinary Java array. You don't have to specify a size up front; the list manages its capacity behind the scenes.\n\nSuppose the list currently contains two elements, [2, 3], and the backing array is full. When you add a third element:\n\nArrayList allocates a new, larger array — typically the old capacity plus half of it (so 3 in this example, then 4, 6, 9, 13, ...).\n\nIt copies the existing elements into the new array: [2, 3, _, _].\n\nIt writes the new element into the next free slot: [2, 3, 4, _]. Subsequent adds reuse the extra space without another allocation.\n\nBecause each resize copies all existing elements, a single add is occasionally O(n), but averaged across many adds the cost is O(1) amortized.\n\nRemoval works the other way around:\n\nArrayList searches the backing array for the element to remove. By index this is O(1); by value it is O(n).\n\nAfter locating the element, it shifts every element to the right of that position one slot to the left so the array stays contiguous.\n\nReads by index are always O(1) thanks to the contiguous backing array."}, {"number": 70, "question": "Although inheritance is a popular OOP concept, composition is often a better choice. Why?", "answer": "Inheritance is rigid; composition tends to be more flexible. The main reasons to prefer composition over inheritance are:\n\nMultiple sources of behavior: Java does not allow a class to extend more than one superclass. If you need behavior from several places (say, both a Reader and a Writer), composition lets you hold both as private fields and delegate to them.\n\nEncapsulation: composition keeps you in control of the public surface of your class. Inheritance exposes every public and protected member of the superclass and tightly couples your class to its internals.\n\nTestability: a composed dependency can be replaced with a mock or stub in tests. A super-class is generally much harder to substitute.\n\nCoupling: composition is loosely coupled — only the methods you actually call create a dependency. Inheritance is tightly coupled, so small changes in the superclass can ripple into every subclass.\n\nConcrete example. Start with inheritance:\n\npackage comparison;\npublic class Top {\n  public int start() { return 0; }\n}\nclass Bottom extends Top {\n  public int stop() { return 0; }\n}\n\nNow Top is updated to add a stop method of its own:\n\npublic class Top {\n  public int start() { return 0; }\n  public void stop() {}\n}\n\nBottom no longer compiles: its stop() method has an incompatible return type with the new stop() in Top. The fix requires changing one of the two classes. With composition the same situation is harmless:\n\nclass Bottom {\n  Top par = new Top();\n  public int stop() {\n    par.start();\n    par.stop();\n    return 0;\n  }\n}\n\nBottom does not inherit anything from Top, so adding a method to Top has no effect on it."}, {"number": 71, "question": "What is the difference between the >> and >>> operators in Java?", "answer": "Both are right-shift operators. The difference is what they do with the sign bit.\n\n>> (signed/arithmetic right shift): shifts each bit one position to the right and fills the vacated leftmost positions with copies of the original sign bit. The sign of the result matches the sign of the input.\n\n>>> (unsigned/logical right shift): also shifts each bit one position to the right, but always fills the vacated leftmost positions with zeros. The result is always non-negative when viewed as an unsigned value, even if the input was negative.\n\nExample, with num1 = 8 and num2 = -8 represented as 32-bit binary:\n\nnum1 = 00000000 00000000 00000000 00001000\nnum2 = 11111111 11111111 11111111 11111000\n\n8 >> 1 and -8 >> 1:\nnum1 = 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000100\nnum2 = 11111111 11111111 11111111 11111100\n\n8 >>> 1 and -8 >>> 1:\nnum1 = 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000100\nnum2 = 01111111 11111111 11111111 11111100"}, {"number": 72, "question": "What are composition and aggregation, and how do they differ?", "answer": "Both composition and aggregation describe a HAS-A relationship between classes — one class holds a reference to another as part of its state. The difference is in the lifetime coupling between the container and the contained object.\n\nComposition is a strong association. The contained object's lifetime is tied to the container's: if the container is destroyed, the contained objects are destroyed with it. Example: a University class owns its Department objects. The departments only exist as part of that university; if the university is gone, the departments are gone too.\n\nAggregation is a weak association. The container holds a reference to the contained object, but does not own it. If the container goes away, the contained object can continue to exist and be referenced by something else. Example: a Department class refers to Professor objects. If the department is dissolved, the professors can be reassigned to another department — they outlive the department."}, {"number": 73, "question": "How is creating a String with new() different from creating one as a literal?", "answer": "When you create a String as a literal, Java interns it in the String constant pool. Two literals with the same contents share a single underlying object, so reference equality (==) returns true:\n\npublic boolean checking() {\n  String first = \"QuizBit\";\n  String second = \"QuizBit\";\n  return first == second; // true — both refer to the same pooled object\n}\n\nWhen you create a String with new String(...), the constructor always allocates a fresh object on the heap, even if an identical string already exists in the pool. Reference equality is therefore false:\n\npublic boolean checking() {\n  String first = new String(\"QuizBit\");\n  String second = new String(\"QuizBit\");\n  return first == second; // false — two distinct heap objects\n}\n\nIn both cases first.equals(second) returns true, because equals() compares contents. You can also force pooling explicitly by calling intern() on a String created with new."}, {"number": 74, "question": "How is the new operator different from Class.newInstance()?", "answer": "Both produce a new instance, but they work at different times. Use new when you know the concrete class at compile time:\n\nMyClass obj = new MyClass();\n\nUse newInstance() (via reflection) when the class name is only known at runtime — for example, when it comes from a command-line argument, a configuration file, or a database row:\n\nClass<?> cls = Class.forName(className);\nObject obj = cls.getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance();\n\nBecause the class might not exist at runtime, or might lack a suitable constructor, the reflective form throws checked exceptions (ClassNotFoundException, NoSuchMethodException, InstantiationException, IllegalAccessException, InvocationTargetException) that you have to catch or declare. The older Class.newInstance() method itself has been deprecated since Java 9 in favor of getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance()."}, {"number": 75, "question": "Is it possible to exceed the memory limit in a program despite having a garbage collector?", "answer": "Yes. Garbage collection reclaims memory used by objects that are no longer reachable from the running program, but it can't help with objects that are still referenced.\n\nWhen the JVM needs memory for a new object, the garbage collector tries to free space by collecting unreachable objects. If after collection there still isn't enough room, the JVM throws OutOfMemoryError.\n\nThe most common cause of running out of heap is unintentional retention — references that keep growing without ever being released. Caches, listener lists, and collections that are appended to in a loop without bound are typical culprits. The example below exhausts the heap in seconds even though every iteration is well-formed:\n\nList<String> example = new LinkedList<>();\nwhile (true) {\n  example.add(new String(\"Memory Limit Exceeded\"));\n}\n\nMake sure to drop references to objects you no longer need, so the garbage collector can actually reclaim them."}, {"number": 76, "question": "Why is synchronization necessary? Explain with an example.", "answer": "Synchronization lets multiple threads safely share mutable state. When several threads access the same data without coordination, their operations can interleave in surprising ways and leave the data in an inconsistent state — a class of bugs known as race conditions.\n\nFor example, imagine a counter that records the number of requests made to a URL.\n\nWithout synchronization:\n\npackage anonymous;\npublic class Counting {\n  private int counter;\n  public int increase() {\n    counter = counter + 1;\n    return counter;\n  }\n}\n\nSuppose two threads both read counter when it equals 10. Each computes 10 + 1 = 11 locally and writes 11 back. The final value is 11 instead of the expected 12 — one of the increments is silently lost.\n\nAdding synchronized to increase() ensures that only one thread at a time runs the method against any given Counting instance:\n\npackage anonymous;\npublic class Counting {\n  private int counter;\n  public synchronized int increase() {\n    counter = counter + 1;\n    return counter;\n  }\n}\n\nNow if thread 1 sees 10 and increments to 11, thread 2 will subsequently see 11 and increment to 12, and so on. (In real code you would more often reach for java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicInteger for a simple counter like this.)"}, {"number": 77, "question": "In the code below, what does ... mean?", "answer": "public void fooBarMethod(String... variables) {\n  // method code\n}\n\nThree trailing dots after a parameter type denote varargs (variable arguments), introduced in Java 5. They let the method accept any number of arguments of the given type — the compiler automatically bundles them into an array.\n\nThe method above can be called in any of these ways:\n\nfooBarMethod(\"foo\", \"bar\");\nfooBarMethod(\"foo\", \"bar\", \"boo\");\nfooBarMethod(new String[]{\"foo\", \"var\", \"boo\"});\n\nInside the method, variables is a String[] and can be iterated like any other array:\n\npublic void myMethod(String... variables) {\n  for (String variable : variables) {\n    // business logic\n  }\n}\n\nVarargs must be the last parameter in the method signature, and a method can have at most one varargs parameter."}, {"number": 78, "question": "What is the output of this Java program, and what does it tell you about class initialization order?", "answer": "class QuizBit {\n  int i;\n  static int j;\n\n  { System.out.println(\" Instance Block 1. Value of i = \" + i); }\n  static {\n    System.out.println(\" Static Block 1. Value of j = \" + j);\n    method_2();\n  }\n  { i = 5; }\n  static { j = 10; }\n\n  QuizBit() { System.out.println(\" Welcome to QuizBit \"); }\n\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    QuizBit ib = new QuizBit();\n  }\n  public void method_1() { System.out.println(\" Instance method. \"); }\n\n  static { System.out.println(\" Static Block 2. Value of j = \" + j); }\n  {\n    System.out.println(\" Instance Block 2. Value of i = \" + i);\n    method_1();\n  }\n  public static void method_2() { System.out.println(\" Static method. \"); }\n}\n\nOutput:\nStatic Block 1. Value of j = 0\nStatic method.\nStatic Block 2. Value of j = 10\nInstance Block 1. Value of i = 0\nInstance Block 2. Value of i = 5\nInstance method.\nWelcome to QuizBit\n\nThe order is fixed by the language. A Java class is initialized like this:\n\nStatic fields and static initializer blocks run once, in source order, when the class is loaded. (Static fields are first assigned their default values, then their declared values.)\n\nThe main method (or whichever static method triggered loading) then begins executing.\n\nFor every new instance created thereafter, instance fields and instance initializer blocks run in source order, again with default-then-declared assignment.\n\nFinally the constructor body runs.\n\nWalking through the code:\n\nOn class load the JVM identifies the static members (j, the three static blocks, main, and method_2) and gives j its default value 0. It then executes the static blocks in source order: Static Block 1 prints j == 0 and calls method_2 (\"Static method.\"). The next static block sets j = 10. The third static block prints j == 10.\n\nmain runs and creates a QuizBit instance.\n\nInstance initialization begins. i defaults to 0, then Instance Block 1 prints i == 0. The next instance block sets i = 5. Instance Block 2 prints i == 5 and calls method_1.\n\nFinally the constructor runs and prints \" Welcome to QuizBit \"."}, {"number": 79, "question": "Explain System.out.println().", "answer": "System.out.println() prints a line to the console. Each part of the call refers to a different element of the standard library:\n\nSystem is a class in java.lang.\n\nout is a public static field on System of type PrintStream — it represents the standard output stream.\n\nprintln(...) is a method on PrintStream that writes its argument followed by a line terminator.\n\nPutting it together: System.out.println(\"hi\") asks the PrintStream stored in System.out to print the line \"hi\"."}, {"number": 80, "question": "Can you explain the Java thread lifecycle?", "answer": "A Java thread moves through a small set of well-defined states:\n\nNEW: the Thread object has been created but start() has not yet been called.\n\nRUNNABLE: start() has been called, so the thread is eligible to run. The scheduler decides when it actually gets CPU time. A thread coming back from sleeping or waiting also returns to the runnable state before resuming.\n\nRUNNING: an informal sub-state of RUNNABLE in which the scheduler has assigned the thread to a CPU and run() is actively executing. The Thread.State enum doesn't include this as a separate value — Java reports it as RUNNABLE.\n\nBLOCKED / WAITING / TIMED_WAITING: the thread is alive but cannot proceed.\nBLOCKED — waiting to enter a synchronized block because another thread holds the monitor.\nWAITING — waiting indefinitely for another thread (Object.wait(), Thread.join(), LockSupport.park()).\nTIMED_WAITING — waiting for a fixed amount of time (Thread.sleep(), wait(timeout), etc.).\n\nTERMINATED: run() has returned (normally or via an unhandled exception). The thread is no longer alive and cannot be restarted."}, {"number": 81, "question": "What is the trade-off between using an ordered array and an unordered array?", "answer": "An ordered array supports binary search, so lookup is O(log n) — much faster than the O(n) linear scan required for an unordered array.\n\nThe trade-off is insertion cost. Inserting into an ordered array requires finding the right position and shifting every later element to make room — O(n) per insert. An unordered array, if you don't care where new elements go, can simply append in O(1).\n\nPick the structure that matches your workload: if reads dominate, an ordered array is usually faster overall; if writes dominate, an unordered array (or a different structure altogether, such as a hash table) may be a better fit."}, {"number": 82, "question": "Is it possible to import the same class or package twice in Java, and what happens at runtime?", "answer": "Yes, the compiler accepts redundant imports — they just don't do anything useful. The JVM loads any given class or interface exactly once per ClassLoader regardless of how many import statements mention it, so duplicates have no runtime effect (and most IDEs flag them as a warning)."}, {"number": 83, "question": "If a package has sub-packages, does importing the parent also import the sub-packages? For example, does importing com.myMainPackage.* also import com.myMainPackage.mySubPackage.*?", "answer": "No. Each package must be imported explicitly. Writing import com.myMainPackage.*; brings in the classes declared directly in com.myMainPackage but not the classes declared in any of its sub-packages. To use a class from a sub-package, you have to import that sub-package (or use the fully qualified class name)."}, {"number": 84, "question": "Will the finally block run if System.exit(0) is the last statement of the try block?", "answer": "No. System.exit() asks the JVM to terminate immediately, so control never returns to the enclosing method — the finally block is skipped. This is the canonical exception to the rule that finally always runs."}, {"number": 85, "question": "What are marker interfaces in Java?", "answer": "Marker interfaces (also called tagging interfaces) are interfaces that declare no methods or constants. They exist purely to mark a class as belonging to some category, so that other code — the compiler, the JVM, or a library — can identify those classes at runtime. Examples in the standard library include Serializable, Cloneable, and Remote.\n\nModern code often prefers annotations (with retention RUNTIME) over marker interfaces for the same purpose, since annotations can also carry parameters."}, {"number": 86, "question": "What is double-brace initialization in Java?", "answer": "Double-brace initialization is a shorthand for populating a collection (or any object) at the point of construction. Here is the idiom:\n\nimport java.util.HashSet;\nimport java.util.Set;\npublic class IBDoubleBraceDemo {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    Set<String> stringSets = new HashSet<String>() {{\n      add(\"set1\");\n      add(\"set2\");\n      add(\"set3\");\n    }};\n    doSomething(stringSets);\n  }\n  private static void doSomething(Set<String> stringSets) {\n    System.out.println(stringSets);\n  }\n}\n\nThe two pairs of braces do different things:\n\nThe outer braces define an anonymous subclass of HashSet that has access to the parent class's methods (like add).\n\nThe inner braces are an instance initializer block on that subclass; the add() calls run as the new instance is being constructed.\n\nUse it sparingly. Every double-brace initialization creates a new anonymous inner class, which keeps a hidden reference to the enclosing instance, increases class-loading cost, and can cause memory leaks or serialization headaches. List.of(...), Set.of(...), and Map.of(...) (Java 9+) are usually a better choice."}, {"number": 87, "question": "Why is String.length() sometimes said not to return an accurate result?", "answer": "String.length() returns the number of UTF-16 code units in the string, not the number of user-visible characters.\n\nA bit of background. Java's String is stored in UTF-16. Unicode itself defines several concepts that are easy to confuse:\n\nCode point: an integer that identifies a character (or, more precisely, a Unicode scalar value).\n\nCode unit: a fixed-size piece of an encoded representation. UTF-16 uses 16-bit code units.\n\nUnder UTF-16, code points are organized into 17 planes. The first plane — the Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP) — covers U+0000 through U+FFFF and encodes each code point as a single 16-bit unit. The remaining planes cover U+10000 through U+10FFFF (the \"supplementary\" characters, such as most emoji and many CJK characters) and encode each code point as a surrogate pair — two 16-bit units.\n\nSo when a String contains supplementary characters, length() counts each one as 2. For example, a String holding a single emoji that lives outside the BMP returns 2 from length() even though there is only one visible character. This is documented behavior, but it can surprise developers who expect the result to be a character count.\n\nTo count code points instead of code units, use String.codePointCount(0, str.length())."}, {"number": 88, "question": "What does this code print, and why?", "answer": "public class QuizBit {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    System.out.println('b' + 'i' + 't');\n  }\n}\n\nThe output is 319, not \"bit\". The literals 'b', 'i', and 't' are char literals, not String literals. The + operator does not perform String concatenation for chars — it performs numeric addition after promoting each char to int.\n\nThe ASCII values are:\n'b' = 98\n'i' = 105\n't' = 116\n\n98 + 105 + 116 = 319, which is what println receives and prints. To get \"bit\" instead, you would have to use double-quoted string literals or convert at least one operand to a String first."}, {"number": 89, "question": "What are the possible ways to make an object eligible for garbage collection in Java?", "answer": "An object becomes eligible for garbage collection as soon as no live reference can reach it. Three common patterns make that happen:\n\nNull out the reference once you're done with the object:\n\npublic class IBGarbageCollect {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    String s1 = \"Some String\";\n    // s1 still references the object — not eligible yet\n    s1 = null;\n    // now the original object is unreachable and eligible for GC\n  }\n}\n\nReassign the reference to point at a different object. The object originally referenced — if no other reference still points at it — becomes eligible:\n\npublic class IBGarbageCollect {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    String s1 = \"To Garbage Collect\";\n    String s2 = \"Another Object\";\n    System.out.println(s1);\n    s1 = s2;\n    // \"To Garbage Collect\" has no live references — eligible for GC\n  }\n}\n\nIsland of isolation: a group of objects that reference each other but are not reachable from any GC root. The garbage collector recognizes that the whole island is unreachable as a whole and reclaims every object in it:\n\npublic class IBGarbageCollect {\n  IBGarbageCollect ib;\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    IBGarbageCollect ibgc1 = new IBGarbageCollect();\n    IBGarbageCollect ibgc2 = new IBGarbageCollect();\n    ibgc1.ib = ibgc2; // ibgc1 points to ibgc2\n    ibgc2.ib = ibgc1; // ibgc2 points to ibgc1\n    ibgc1 = null;\n    ibgc2 = null;\n    // ibgc1 and ibgc2 still reference each other, but nothing outside the pair references\n    // them — they form an island of isolation and both are eligible for GC.\n  }\n}"}, {"number": 90, "question": "How many objects are eligible for garbage collection in this program?", "answer": "class Main {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    int[][] num = new int[3][];\n    num[0] = new int[5];\n    num[1] = new int[2];\n    num[2] = new int[3];\n    num[2] = new int[5];\n    num[0] = new int[4];\n    num[1] = new int[3];\n    num = new int[2][];\n  }\n}\n\nSeven objects become eligible for garbage collection.\n\nThree of them come from the reassignments num[0] = new int[4], num[1] = new int[3], and num[2] = new int[5]. Each of these reassignments orphans the int[5], int[2], and int[3] arrays that the corresponding slot used to hold.\n\nThe other four come from num = new int[2][]. After this line, the original 3-element outer array — and the three int[4], int[3], int[5] arrays it referenced — are no longer reachable. That's 1 + 3 = 4 more objects.\n\n3 + 4 = 7 objects in total."}, {"number": 91, "question": "What is the recommended way to inject dependencies, and why?", "answer": "There's no single right answer — the choice depends on whether the dependency is mandatory or optional. The typical recommendation is:\n\nUse constructor injection for mandatory dependencies. The class cannot be instantiated without them, the fields can be declared final, and the object is fully initialized before anyone gets a reference to it.\n\nUse setter injection for optional dependencies. Setters let the caller supply only the values they actually need without complicating the constructor signature.\n\nConstructor injection is generally preferred where possible because it produces objects that are immutable in their dependencies and easier to test."}, {"number": 92, "question": "How do you set the scope of a Spring bean, and what scopes does Spring support?", "answer": "You set a bean's scope either with the @Scope annotation in code or with the scope attribute on the <bean> element in an XML configuration file.\n\nSpring supports five built-in scopes:\n\nsingleton (default) — one shared instance per Spring container.\n\nprototype — a new instance every time the bean is requested.\n\nrequest — one instance per HTTP request (web-aware contexts only).\n\nsession — one instance per HTTP session (web-aware contexts only).\n\napplication (formerly global-session in older Spring versions) — one instance per ServletContext."}, {"number": 93, "question": "What are the categories of Java design patterns?", "answer": "The Gang of Four design patterns commonly taught in Java are split into three categories, with a fourth (J2EE patterns) often added for enterprise applications.\n\nCreational patterns — how objects are constructed:\nFactory Method\nAbstract Factory\nBuilder\nPrototype\nSingleton\n\nStructural patterns — how classes and objects are composed:\nAdapter\nBridge\nComposite\nDecorator\nFacade\nFlyweight\nProxy\n(Filter is sometimes added here as well.)\n\nBehavioral patterns — how objects interact and distribute responsibility:\nChain of Responsibility\nCommand\nInterpreter\nIterator\nMediator\nMemento\nObserver\nState\nStrategy\nTemplate Method\nVisitor\n\nJ2EE patterns — Java EE-specific architectural patterns:\nMVC\nData Access Object (DAO)\nFront Controller\nIntercepting Filter\nTransfer Object"}, {"number": 94, "question": "What is a memory leak, and what are some common causes in Java?", "answer": "A memory leak in Java happens when objects that the program no longer needs remain reachable from a GC root and therefore cannot be reclaimed by the garbage collector. Over time the heap fills with these zombie objects and the application slows down or fails with OutOfMemoryError.\n\nCommon causes include:\n\nCaches with no eviction policy that grow without bound.\n\nListener or callback lists from which entries are never removed, so listeners keep their subjects alive forever.\n\nStatic collections (or static fields in general) that are appended to over the lifetime of the application.\n\nCustom data structures that hold on to references after they're logically removed (for example, an array-backed stack that doesn't null out popped slots).\n\nThreadLocal values that are not cleared when the thread is returned to a thread pool.\n\nClassLoader leaks, where a web application reloads but classes from the old class loader remain referenced by some object in the JVM (often via ThreadLocal or JDBC drivers)."}, {"number": 95, "question": "If a thread is holding a lock, does calling sleep() on it release the lock?", "answer": "No. Thread.sleep() pauses the thread for the specified duration but does not release any locks (monitors) it holds. Other threads trying to acquire those locks have to wait until the sleeping thread wakes up and releases them normally.\n\nThe method that does release the monitor is Object.wait()."}, {"number": 96, "question": "Write a Java program to check whether a given string is a palindrome, using recursion.", "answer": "/*\n * Java program to check whether a given input string is a palindrome, using recursion.\n */\nimport java.util.*;\npublic class QuizBit {\n  public static void main(String args[]) {\n    Scanner s = new Scanner(System.in);\n    String word = s.nextLine();\n    System.out.println(\"Is \" + word + \" palindrome? - \" + isWordPalindrome(word));\n  }\n  public static boolean isWordPalindrome(String word) {\n    String reverseWord = getReverseWord(word);\n    return word.equals(reverseWord);\n  }\n  public static String getReverseWord(String word) {\n    if (word == null || word.isEmpty()) {\n      return word;\n    }\n    return word.charAt(word.length() - 1) + getReverseWord(word.substring(0, word.length() - 1));\n  }\n}"}, {"number": 97, "question": "Write a Java program to print the Fibonacci series using recursion.", "answer": "class QuizBit {\n  public static void printFibonacci(int val1, int val2, int num) {\n    if (num == 0) return; // base case\n    System.out.print((val1 + val2) + \" \");\n    printFibonacci(val2, val1 + val2, --num);\n  }\n  public static void main(String args[]) {\n    System.out.println(\" *** Fibonacci Series *** \");\n    System.out.print(\"0 1 \");        // print the first two values\n    printFibonacci(0, 1, 10);          // print the next 10 values\n  }\n}\n\nThe program prints the first two Fibonacci numbers (0 and 1) directly and then uses the recursive helper printFibonacci to emit the next n numbers, passing the previous two values forward at each step."}, {"number": 98, "question": "Write a Java program to check whether two strings are anagrams.", "answer": "Idea: two strings are anagrams if and only if they have the same length and the same characters. Sorting both as char arrays and comparing them is the simplest correct approach.\n\nimport java.util.Arrays;\nimport java.util.Scanner;\npublic class QuizBit {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    Scanner s = new Scanner(System.in);\n    System.out.print(\"First String: \");\n    String string1 = s.nextLine();\n    System.out.print(\"Second String: \");\n    String string2 = s.nextLine();\n    if (string1.length() == string2.length()) {\n      char[] characterArray1 = string1.toCharArray();\n      char[] characterArray2 = string2.toCharArray();\n      Arrays.sort(characterArray1);\n      Arrays.sort(characterArray2);\n      boolean isAnagram = Arrays.equals(characterArray1, characterArray2);\n      System.out.println(\"Anagram: \" + isAnagram);\n    } else {\n      System.out.println(\"Anagram: false\");\n    }\n  }\n}"}, {"number": 99, "question": "Write a Java program to find the factorial of a given number.", "answer": "public class FindFactorial {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    int num = 10;\n    long factorialResult = 1L;\n    for (int i = 1; i <= num; ++i) {\n      factorialResult *= i;\n    }\n    System.out.println(\"Factorial: \" + factorialResult);\n  }\n}"}, {"number": 100, "question": "Given an array containing distinct numbers from 1 to n with one number missing, write an efficient Java program to find the missing number.", "answer": "Idea: the sum of the first n natural numbers is n * (n + 1) / 2. Compute the actual sum of the array and subtract it from the expected sum; the difference is the missing number. This runs in O(n) time and O(1) extra space.\n\npublic class IBMissingNumberProblem {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    int[] array = {4, 3, 8, 7, 5, 2, 6};\n    int missingNumber = findMissingNum(array);\n    System.out.println(\"Missing Number is \" + missingNumber);\n  }\n  public static int findMissingNum(int[] array) {\n    int n = array.length + 1;\n    int sumOfFirstNNums = n * (n + 1) / 2;\n    int actualSumOfArr = 0;\n    for (int i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {\n      actualSumOfArr += array[i];\n    }\n    return sumOfFirstNNums - actualSumOfArr;\n  }\n}"}, {"number": 101, "question": "Write a Java program to check whether a number is a magic number. A number is a magic number if repeatedly summing its digits eventually yields 1.", "answer": "Example, starting with 163:\nStep 1: 1 + 6 + 3 = 10\nStep 2: 1 + 0 = 1\n163 is therefore a magic number.\n\npublic class IBMagicNumber {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    int num = 163;\n    int sumOfDigits = 0;\n    while (num > 0 || sumOfDigits > 9) {\n      if (num == 0) {\n        num = sumOfDigits;\n        sumOfDigits = 0;\n      }\n      sumOfDigits += num % 10;\n      num /= 10;\n    }\n    if (sumOfDigits == 1) {\n      System.out.println(\"Magic number\");\n    } else {\n      System.out.println(\"Not magic number\");\n    }\n  }\n}"}, {"number": 102, "question": "Write a Java program that defines and throws a custom exception.", "answer": "class QuizBit {\n  public static void main(String args[]) throws CustomException {\n    throw new CustomException(\" This is my custom exception \");\n  }\n}\nclass CustomException extends Exception {\n  public CustomException(String message) {\n    super(message);\n  }\n}\n\nCustomException extends Exception (which makes it a checked exception) and forwards the message through super(message) so that getMessage() and the stack trace print it correctly. The main method declares throws CustomException rather than catching it, so the JVM ultimately prints the stack trace."}, {"number": 103, "question": "Write a Java program to reverse a string.", "answer": "class QuizBit {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    String str = \"Welcome to QuizBit\";\n    int i = 0, j = str.length() - 1;\n    char[] revString = new char[j + 1];\n    while (i <= j) {\n      revString[j] = str.charAt(i);\n      revString[i] = str.charAt(j);\n      i++;\n      j--;\n    }\n    System.out.println(\"Reversed String = \" + String.valueOf(revString));\n  }\n}\n\nTwo pointers — i starting at the beginning and j starting at the end — walk toward each other. At each step the program copies the character at one end into the other end of a new output array. When the pointers meet, the reversal is complete."}, {"number": 104, "question": "Write a Java program that rotates a square matrix 90° clockwise, reading the matrix from user input.", "answer": "import java.util.Scanner;\npublic class QuizBit {\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);\n    System.out.print(\"Enter size of array: \");\n    int n = sc.nextInt();\n    int[][] a = new int[n][n];\n    System.out.print(\"Enter \" + n * n + \" elements: \");\n    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)\n      for (int j = 0; j < n; j++)\n        a[i][j] = sc.nextInt();\n\n    System.out.print(\"\\nArray Before Rotation\\n\\n\");\n    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n      for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) System.out.print(a[i][j] + \" \");\n      System.out.println();\n    }\n    System.out.println();\n\n    // Transpose in place.\n    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)\n      for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {\n        int temp = a[i][j];\n        a[i][j] = a[j][i];\n        a[j][i] = temp;\n      }\n\n    // Reverse each row.\n    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n      for (int l = 0, r = n - 1; l < r; l++, r--) {\n        int temp = a[i][l];\n        a[i][l] = a[i][r];\n        a[i][r] = temp;\n      }\n    }\n\n    System.out.println(\"Array After Rotation -\\n\");\n    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n      for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) System.out.print(a[i][j] + \" \");\n      System.out.println();\n    }\n  }\n}\n\nRotating a square matrix 90° clockwise can be done in two steps: transpose the matrix (swap a[i][j] with a[j][i] for j ≥ i), then reverse each row. Together, these two operations produce the rotated matrix without needing a second matrix."}, {"number": 105, "question": "Write a Java program that, given a number, prints all pairs of prime numbers that sum to it.", "answer": "Example:\nInput: 18\nOutput:\n18 = 13 + 5\n18 = 11 + 7\n\npublic class QuizBit {\n  // Returns 0 if num is prime, 1 otherwise.\n  private static int checkPrime(int num) {\n    if (num < 2) return 1;\n    for (int i = 2; i <= num / 2; i++) {\n      if (num % i == 0) return 1;\n    }\n    return 0;\n  }\n\n  private static void find(int num) {\n    for (int i = 2; i <= num / 2; i++) {\n      if (checkPrime(i) == 0 && checkPrime(num - i) == 0) {\n        System.out.println(num + \" = \" + (num - i) + \" + \" + i);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    find(18);\n  }\n}\n\nFor each i from 2 up to n/2 the program checks whether both i and n - i are prime; if so, it prints the pair. Iterating only up to n/2 avoids printing each pair twice."}, {"number": 106, "question": "Write a Java program that solves the Tower of Hanoi problem.", "answer": "public class QuizBit {\n  // Recursive solver for Tower of Hanoi.\n  private static void TOH(char source, char auxiliary, char destination, int numOfDisks) {\n    if (numOfDisks > 0) {\n      TOH(source, destination, auxiliary, numOfDisks - 1);\n      System.out.println(\"Move 1 disk from \" + source + \" to \" + destination);\n      TOH(auxiliary, source, destination, numOfDisks - 1);\n    }\n  }\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    TOH('A', 'B', 'C', 3);\n  }\n}\n\nThe recursive idea is: to move n disks from source to destination using auxiliary, first move the top n − 1 disks from source to auxiliary, then move the bottom disk from source to destination, and finally move the n − 1 disks from auxiliary to destination."}, {"number": 107, "question": "Implement binary search in Java using recursion.", "answer": "public class Main {\n  // Recursive binary search.\n  private static boolean binarySearch(int[] arr, int low, int high, int key) {\n    if (low > high) return false; // base case: range is empty\n    int mid = (low + high) / 2;\n    if (arr[mid] == key) return true;            // found in the middle\n    if (key < arr[mid])                         // search left half\n      return binarySearch(arr, low, mid - 1, key);\n    return binarySearch(arr, mid + 1, high, key); // search right half\n  }\n  public static void main(String[] args) {\n    int[] arr = {2, 5, 9, 13, 17, 21, 30};\n    if (binarySearch(arr, 0, arr.length - 1, 30))\n      System.out.println(\" Element Found. \");\n    else\n      System.out.println(\" Element Not Found.\");\n  }\n}\n\nAt each step the algorithm checks the middle element of the current range. If it matches the key, the search succeeds. Otherwise it recurses on whichever half could still contain the key, halving the search space each time — which is why binary search runs in O(log n) time."}];
